      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "ecf40676f379c28bc50387d3333fa104",
      "text": "# Countryside and Rights of Way Act 2000 (CROW)"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1a1ea36e896cf0bd3ba536ced9838ef5",
      "text": "Other than for those commons covered by the 1925 law of property Act, the public did not have the right to use or enjoy common land if they were not a commoner. However, the [[Countryside and Rights of Way Act 2000]] gave the public the [[Freedom to roam]] freely on all registered common land in England and Wales.[http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/ourwork/access/openaccess/default.aspx Open Access land]  The new rights were introduced region by region through England and Wales, with completion in 2005. Maps showing accessible areas have been produced, and are available online as \"open access maps\" produced by Natural England.<ref>[http://www.openaccess.naturalengland.org.uk/wps/portal/oasys/maps/MapSearch Open access maps at Natural England]</ref> Commons are included in the public access land now shown on the [[Ordnance Survey]] Explorer Maps."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "c1972a1f662d5bfe8a6700fc181aa8d0",
      "text": "# Commons Act 2006"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "62eb7cc3e3cd8473632634ecc1fb57be",
      "text": "The Commons Act 2006 is an important new piece of legislation.<ref>[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2006/26/section/15 Commons act 2006]</ref>"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "be7dfdb55a558c2e03cb35d67e258083",
      "text": "The Act:\n* Enables commons to be managed more sustainably by commoners and landowners working together through commons councils with powers to regulate grazing and other agricultural activities\n* Provides better protection for common land and greens - this includes reinforcing existing protections against abuse, encroachment and unauthorised development\n* Recognises that the protection of common land has to be proportionate to the harm caused and that some specified works can be carried out without the need for consent\n* Requires commons registration authorities to bring their registers up-to-date by recording past changes affecting the registers during a ‘transitional period’, and to keep the registers up-to-date by recording new changes affecting the registers - commons registration authorities will have new powers to correct many of the mistakes in the registers\n* Sets out new, clearer criteria for the registration of town or village greens\n* Prohibits the severance of common rights, preventing commoners from selling, leasing or letting their rights away from the property to which rights are attached,([https://www.gov.uk/common-land-management-protection-and-registering-to-use HMG Guide to the 2006 act]) though, in certain circumstances temporary severance is permitted for up to 2 years (renewable)"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "318c43ecae68ae2c6d66ae02cc84b523",
      "text": "Several hundred square kilometres of ‘waste land’ that was eligible for registration under the 1965 Commons Registration Act was not, in fact, finally registered. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "903074c236cb0137",
      "text": "As a consequence, it ceased to be recognised as common land. A partial remedy for this defect in the earlier legislation is provided by the Commons Act 2006. Under Schedule 2, 4 of the Act, applications that failed under the original registration process may, in certain circumstances, be reconsidered – offering, in effect, a second chance for the land to be confirmed (‘re-registered’) as common. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "6fbda307a7a38f93",
      "text": "Land that is re-registered in this way will enjoy the special legal protection afforded to common land. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2c6ee2abf85b915e",
      "text": "It will also be subject to the public right of access introduced by the Countryside and Rights of Way Act 2000; or, may qualify as a section 193 ‘urban’ common (in which case, it would also be subject to a right of access for horse-riders) - [http://www.oss.org.uk/what-we-do/commons/the-commons-act-2006/ oss.org.uk]"
    }
